land, Wisconsin|Ashland]]. | |- |[[Noquebay (shipwreck)|''Noquebay'']] |2 October 1905 |The wooden [[schooner]] caught fire and sank in Lake Superior off the coast of [[Stockton Island]], in [[Chequamegon Bay]]. | |- |[[Phoenix (steamship)|''Phoenix'']] |21 November 1847 |Wooden steamship that caught fire from over-stoked boilers and burned to the waterline off the coast of Sheboygan, WI, killing at least 190 but perhaps more than 250 of the nearly 300 people on board. 40 people survived in lifeboats and three were rescued from the water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baillod.com/shipwreck/projects/sheboygan/phoenix.htm|title=Shipwrecks|accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref> | |- |''[[Pretoria (ship)|Pretoria]]'' |2 September 1905 |The wooden [[schooner]] sank in a storm on [[Lake Superior]] near the [[Apostle Islands]] | |- |''Senator'' |30 October 1929 |A collision with the ''Marquette'' in a dense fog sank the Senator off Port Washington in Lake Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christmaswhistler.web44.net/smithHistory/1929-SenatorMarquetteCollision.html|title=Save All but 7 Off Sunken Senator|publisher=Unknown|date=c. 1929}}</ref> | |- |''[[Sevona (shipwreck)|Sevona]]'' |2 September 1905 |The [[steamboat]] sank in a storm on [[Lake Superior]] near [[Sand Island (Wisconsin)|Sand Island]]. | |- |''[[Tennie and Laura (schooner)|Tennie and Laura]]'' |2 August 1903 |The [[schooner]] was sailing from [[Muskegon, Michigan]] to Milwaukee carrying a cargo of lumber worth roughly $500 at the time. The ship was crewed by two men, Captain John Sather and First Mate Charles Nordbach. About {{convert|9|nmi|km}} from [[Port Washington, Wisconsin|Port Washington]] she was caught in a storm. The ship eventually capsized, and Mate Morbach died. | |}
