{{Orphan|date=August 2015}}

Although never given an official name, a '''"Mammy memorial"''' was a proposed memorial to be located in the [[District of Columbia]] that would have honored [[mammy archetype|mammys]] in the [[United States]]. Proposed by a Southern Congressman and immediately condemned by African Americans and other groups, the monument would have been located along [[Massachusetts Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue]].<ref name=Horwitz>{{cite news|last1=Horwitz|first1=Tony|title=The Mammy Washington Almost Had|url=http://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2013/05/the-mammy-washington-almost-had/276431/|accessdate=17 August 2015|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|date=31 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=Auslander>{{cite web|last1=Auslander|first1=Mark|title=We've Come a Long Way from the Effort to Memorialize the Slave Mammy|url=http://historynewsnetwork.org/article/142126|publisher=[[George Mason University]]|accessdate=17 August 2015|date=29 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=Matthews>{{cite web|last1=Matthews|first1=Lopez|title=Celebrating the Faithful Colored Mammies of the South|url=http://blogs.archives.gov/blackhistoryblog/2013/04/04/celebrating-the-faithful-mammies-of-the-south/|publisher=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|accessdate=17 August 2015|date=4 April 2013}}</ref>

