a|Savannah]] and the [[Province of Georgia]] were founded by [[James Oglethorpe]]. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 1745 || July 19 || ''[[Northeast Coast Campaign (1745)|Northeast Coast Campaign]]'': [[Wabanaki Confederacy]] forces raided towns in northeastern [[New England]], killing one and taking two hostages. |- | September 5 || ''Northeast Coast Campaign (1745)'': [[Wabanaki Confederacy]] forces killed and scalped two people in what is now [[Thomaston, Maine]] in their last raid of the campaign. |- | November 28 || ''[[Raid on Saratoga]]'': [[Kingdom of France|French]] and indigenous forces burned [[Saratoga, New York]], killing thirty and capturing as many as one hundred [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] colonists. |- | 1749 || || The [[Province of Georgia]] overturned its ban on slavery |- | rowspan="6" valign="top" | 1750 || January 22 || [[Hardwick Township, New Jersey]] was chartered. |- | January 27 || [[Cumberland County, Pennsylvania]] was created from the partition of [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]]. |- | March 3 || [[Stafford Township, New Jersey]] was chartered. |- | June 11 || [[Kent County, Rhode Island]] was established from the partition of [[Providence County, Rhode Island]]. |- | June 24 || The [[Iron Act]], which eliminated tariffs on iron imported into [[United Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]] from [[British America|America]] and limited American manufacturing capacity, came into force. |- | November 6 || Governor [[Jonathan Law]] of [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut]] died. His deputy [[Roger Wolcott (Connecticut)]] succeeded him as acting governor. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1752 || June 15 || [[Benjamin Franklin]]'s [[kite experiment]] took place. |}
