contracts and charters. |- | December 14 || [[Alabama]] becomes the 22nd state. |- | rowspan="46" valign="top" | 1820 || January 18 || [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] [[William S. Archer]] was seated in the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] representing [[Virginia's 17th congressional district]] following a special election the fill the vacancy left by the resignation of [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[James Pleasants]]. |- | February 1 || [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|congressman]] [[James Johnson (Virginia congressman)]] of [[Virginia's 20th congressional district]] resigned following his appointment to become collector of customs at [[Norfolk, Virginia]]. |- | February 10 || [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|representative]] [[George Strother]] of [[Virginia's 10th congressional district]] resigned. |- | February 16 || [[Charles Kinsey]] was seated in the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] representing [[New Jersey's at-large congressional district]] following a special election to fill the vacancy left by the resignation of fellow [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[John Condit]]. |- | March 1 || [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|congressman]] [[David Walker (Kentucky politician)]] of [[Kentucky's 6th congressional district]] died. |- | March 6 || The [[Missouri Compromise]] was signed into law, providing for the admission of the [[District of Maine]] into the Union as a free state and of the southeastern portion of the [[Missouri Territory]] into the Union as the slave state of [[Missouri]]. It further provided that any additional states admitted out of the territory of the Missouri Territory would be slave or free depending on whether they fell south or north, respectively, of the [[parallel 36°30′ north]]. |- | March 14 || The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] held in a decision in ''[[Handly's Lessee v. Anthony]]'' that where a river is said to be the boundary between two states, the boundary is determined by course of the river at its lowest point. |- | March 15 || The state of [[Maine]] was admitted to the Union. [[Massachusetts's 14th congressional district]] was abolished. |- | Spring || [[Joseph Smith]] claimed to have had his first vision of God in [[Manchester, New York]]. ''See'' [[First Vision]]. |- | April || ''[[New York gubernatorial election, 1820]]'': Incumbent [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[Governor of New York|governor]] [[DeWitt Clinton]] of [[New York (state)|New York]] was reelected with fifty-one percent of the vote. |- | April 24 || The [[Land Act of 1820]] was signed into law, ending the provision of credit to individual buyers of federal land and simultaneously reducing the minimum price and size of tracts that could be sold. |- | 3 May || The seven member [[United States House Committee on Agriculture]], a [[standing committee (United States Congress)|standing committee]] of the [[United States House of Representatives|House]], was established. |- | 12 May || The border between [[Kentucky]] and [[Tennessee]] was extended south between the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]] and [[Tennessee River]]s to the [[parallel 36°30′ north]]. |- | rowspan="5" valign="top" | 15 May || The [[Tenure of Office Act (1820)]] was passed by the [[United States Congress|Congress]], limiting the term in office of civil servants to four years. |- | [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] [[United States Senate|senator]] [[Prentiss Mellen]] of [[Massachusetts]] resigned to become [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Maine Supreme Judicial Court]]. |- | [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[United States Senate|senator]] [[Walter Leake]] of [[Mississippi]] resigned following his appointment to the [[United States Marshals 