the [[governor (United States)|governorship]] of [[Louisiana]]. |- | July 19 || A southern border between [[Alabama]] and [[Mississippi]] was demarked, resolving some confusion over a sliver of land in Mississippi's favor. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | July 26 || [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] [[United States House of Representatives|congressman]] [[James Pindall]] of [[Virginia's 1st congressional district]] resigned. |- | [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|representative]] [[Zabdiel Sampson]] of [[Massachusetts's 8th congressional district]] resigned following his appointment of collector of customs in [[Plymouth, Massachusetts]]. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | August 28 || [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[John C. Gray]] was elected to fill [[James Johnson (Virginia congressman)|Johnson's]] [[United States House of Representatives|House]] seat. |- | ''[[Missouri gubernatorial election, 1820]]'': [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[Alexander McNair]] was elected [[Governor (United States)|governor]] of [[Missouri]] with seventy-two percent of the vote. |- | August 30 || [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[David Holmes (politician)]] was elected to fill the [[United States Senate|Senate]] seat left vacant by [[Walter Leake|Leake's]] resignation. |- | October 10 || ''[[Pennsylvania's 5th congressional district special election, 1820]]'': A special election was held to fill the seat representing [[Pennsylvania's 5th congressional district]] following [[David Fullerton|Fullerton's]] resignation. [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] [[Thomas Grubb McCullough]] won with fifty-one percent of the vote. |- | October 18 || The [[Choctaw]] and the United States concluded the [[Treaty of Doak's Stand]], under which the former ceded roughly half their territory to [[Mississippi]] and agreed to be moved west into modern [[Arkansas]]. |- | October 19 || [[Demo