he [[United States House of Representatives|House]] seat left vacant by [[Zabdiel Sampson|Sampson's]] resignation. |- | December 6 || ''United States presidential election, 1820'': Voting ended. [[James Monroe|Monroe]] was reelected with eighty-one percent of the vote. |- | December || [[Joseph Hiester|Hiester]] resigned his [[United States House of Representatives|House]] seat representing [[Pennsylvania's 7th congressional district]]. |- | December 17 || [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|representative]] [[Nathaniel Hazard]] of [[Rhode Island's at-large congressional district]] died. |- | December 20 || [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] [[United States House of Representatives|congressman]] [[Jesse Slocumb]] of [[North Carolina's 4th congressional district]] died. |- | December 25 || [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] [[United States Senate|senator]] [[James Burrill Jr.]] died. |- | 1821 || August 10 || [[Missouri]] becomes the 24th state. |- | 1823 || || The [[Monroe Doctrine]] is proclaimed. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1824 || || The decision in ''[[Gibbons v. Ogden]]'' affirms federal over state authority in interstate commerce. |- | || ''[[U.S. presidential election]]'': An election is held with inconclusive results. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1825 || || [[John Quincy Adams]] is elected President by the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]; [[John C. Calhoun]] is elected Vice President. |- | || The [[Erie Canal]] is completed. |- | 1826 || July 4 || Former presidents [[Thomas Jefferson|Jefferson]] and [[John Adams]] die within hours of each other; ironically on Independence Day. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 1828 || || ''[[Nullification Crisis]]'': The [[South Carolina Exposition and Protest]] is published. |- | || Construction begins on the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]]. |- | || ''[[U.S. presidential election]]'': [[Andrew Jackson]] is elected President. [[John