[[Category:History of the United States| ]] [[Category:Timelines by country|United States]]

In 1619, 90 young single women from England went to [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] to become wives of the men there, with the women being auctioned off for 150&nbsp;pounds of tobacco each (to be paid to the shipping company), as that was the cost of each woman's travel to America.<ref name="warm ups">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nA2mx68jgTkC&pg=PA31 |title=Voices of a People's History of the&nbsp;... – Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=June 29, 2011|isbn=9780825144608}}</ref> All 90 of them did indeed become wives.<ref name="Weiss2002">{{cite book|author=Sonia Weiss|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Women's History|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=xFEC5tqvXsUC&pg=PA133|year=2002|publisher=Alpha Books|isbn=978-0-02-864201-7|pages=133–}}</ref> The youngest, Jane Dier, had been fifteen or sixteen years old when she left, and one of the oldest, Alice Burges, was twenty-eight.<ref name="Four">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rg7-dOq4ZXQC&pg=PA7 |title=America's Women: Four Hundred Years&nbsp;... – Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= September 1, 2004|accessdate=June 29, 2011|isbn=9780060959814}}</ref> Most of their fathers had died.<ref name="Four"/> Such voyagers were called tobacco brides (or '''King's daughters''', '''Casket girls''', or '''Jamestown brides'''<ref name=Zug>{{cite journal | last = Zug | first = Marcia | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Lonely Colonist Seeks Wife | journal = Duke Journal of Gender Law and Policy | volume = 20 | issue = 85 | pages = 85–125 | publisher = Duke University School of Law | location = Durham, North Carolina | date = Fall 2012 | url = http://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1236&context=djglp | jstor = | issn = | doi = | id = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = | accessdate = 1 April 2013 }}</ref>) and 150 pounds of tobacco was the typical auction price for them, although they usually had the right to refuse the highest bidder.<ref>{{cite book|title=Honor O'Flynn|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uIT2WJEa-LIC&pg=PP11|publisher=JP Bailey Productions|isbn=978-0-9847826-2-8|pages=11–}}</ref> However, tobacco brides were often sent to America against their will, and often sent at very young ages.<ref name="Hersen2013">{{cite book|author=Michel Hersen|title=Handbook of Child Psychopathology|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=RzzSBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA4|date=11 November 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4615-7136-0|pages=4–}}</ref> There were many women and girls who went to America for this purpose (the 1619 voyage being the first), with the women and girls promised free passage and [[Dowry|trousseaus]] for their trouble.<ref name="Hersen2013"/><ref name="Four"/> Many tobacco brides came to America fleeing hardship, but many also suffered once in America.<ref name="ApplebyChang2015">{{cite book|author1=Joyce Appleby|author2=Eileen Chang|author3=Neva Goodwin|title=Encyclopedia of Women in American History|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=DPwvCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA196|date=17 July 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-47162-2|pages=196–}}</ref> 144 tobacco brides were brought to Jamestown by the [[Virginia Company]] between 1619 and 1622, but only six of them lived through their first six years in America.<ref name="ApplebyChang2015"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwhm.org/online-exhibits/jamestownwomen/14.htm |title=NWHM Cyber Exhibit, Building the New World: The Women of Jamestown Settlement |publisher=Nwhm.org |date= |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>
